B12. Discover two bias cases when using a generative AI system.
One bias case is when AI systems make or support decisions that could affect real life people. If an AI system is trained on unfair or incomplete data, it may repeat unfair patterns from the real world.
for example, an AI system used for hiring could learn from past hiring data. If the past data mostly shows men being hired for technical or leadership roles, the AI may learn that males are a better match. This does not mean men are actually better candidates. It means the AI has copied a biased pattern from the data.

Another bias case is facial recognition technology. Facial recognition systems can be biased when they are trained on skin colours.
after looking around, the study done by Buolamwiwni and Timnit Gebru found that commercial facial analysis systems had much higher error rates for darker-skinned women. The study reported error rates of up to 34.7% for darker-skinned females, while the maximum error rate for lighter-skinned males was 0.8%. The study also found that some facial analysis datasets were mostly made up of lighter-skinned subjects.

